[36m(main_task pid=2407745)[0m My previous action is invalid.     If I want to search, I should put the query between <search> and </search>.     If I want to give the final answer, I should put the answer between <answer> and </answer>. Let me try again.
[36m(main_task pid=2407745)[0m  Glide of the pilots into a westward glide begins shortly after the airplane passes the 40-degree zero fuel temperature axis. Once in a glide, the airplane flies the charted glideslope. This line, 40 degrees down from horizontal, extends south along the 40-degree parallel all the way to San Diego. The lower airspeed in the glide is not a cost to economy but is a way to lift the airplane off the top of an approaching cold front which is approaching from the north and northwest. The end of the warm front is roughly where the 80-degree parallel, 80N, lies.  Taxi pattern The pattern for a departure from Los Angeles International Airport is a counterclockwise pattern on which the airplane heads from the right-down position to the left-down position to the left-up position to the right-up position. This is a north-easterly direction and sets the aircraft into a downwind position. During the traffic pattern, the airplane should be above 1,200 feet at the top of descent in order to continue the climb up to 50 feet above the runway during the last phase of the approach to the runway. The west runway is used for departures into the Pacific Ocean. A northbound arrival would use the south runway which is also used by arrivals from the north and west. (Note: The pattern is usually flown counter-clockwise so that a jet that is being vector to land on the west runway starts the departure on the east side of the airport.) Leading edge vortices and ground loops If the landing gear is down and locked and the flaps extended, the airplane cannot climb above 50 feet or more than one knot over the tailwind. This situation is frequently encountered when departing into an offshore wind if the ground run was obstructed, such as on the edge of the runway, by debris, an eddy from the terminal, or a downhill slope to the runway. The ground run can be a few hundred feet or as little as 100 feet. In the latter case, the total climb will be nearly as much as the ground run.
[36m(main_task pid=2407745)[0m Answer:
[36m(main_task pid=2407745)[0m The west runway is used for departures into the Pacific Ocean.
